So Congrio, half of the assistants, and one of the flute girls enter Euclio's house, and Strobilus conducts the others to his master's horne. Soon Euclio returns from the market. He has decided upon an economical wedding, and his pur- chases consist of a little incense and some wreaths to offer to the Lar. At this moment Congrio appears at the door and sends one of his assistants next door to borrow a ‘⁴ bigger pot.'’ The word “pot'’ is a red rag to Eucli0. He rushes into the house and drives everybody out with blows of his cudgel. When the house is clear he digs up the pot of gold, and brings it out concealed under his cloak. Then he sends the cook and his retinue back to their tasks. He soliloquizes:

coming after me in every way. He pretended he was sending*

these cooks as a compliment to me; but he really sent them to steal this gold. And quite as bad as he is that old rooster of mine3 for he came the nearest kind to ruining me. Just where this pot was buried he began scratch-scratching all around with his claws. To make a long story short, he com- pletely soured me. I seized a club and slew that cock, a

thief taken in the very act. I've a notion the cooks had .
